by an emergent generation of anthropologists, these essays address the question of how the identities of peoples whose lives are "marginal" to the modern nation-state have nonetheless been shaped by the impingement of the nation-state on their worlds. Together, these essays make a powerful contribution to understanding how cultural diversity in some parts of Southeast Asia has been reconfigured as modern states have promoted distinctive and powerfully-backed "imaginings" of nations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicityzSoutheast Asia. 0aEthnologyzSoutheast Asia. 0aIndigenous peopleszSoutheast Asia. 0aNationalismzSoutheast Asia. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Jane Monnig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanchetti-Revelli, Lanfranco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrosius, J . Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorvatich, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuipers, Joel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosaldo, Renato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosaldo, Renato, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTsing, Anna Lowenhaupt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022748440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093569340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935693/original  a978-3-11-069042-2 